"""
Christ Layer — 1 Chronicles chapters 9–10
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-1chronicles-9-10.py

Ch9: Post-exile resettlement list, gatekeeper guilds, musicians, Saul genealogy bridge.
Ch10: Saul's death at Gilboa — the failed king whose kingdom transfers to David.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CHRON1_CHRIST_9_10 = {
  "9": {
    "1": "<p>The summary verse — Israel exiled because of their <em>maʿal</em> (unfaithfulness) — frames the entire genealogical prologue as a story of sin and return. This is the biblical exile pattern that Christ definitively fulfills: Isaiah&rsquo;s vision of the true return from exile is not accomplished by Cyrus&rsquo; decree but by the one who announces &ldquo;good news to the poor&rdquo; and &ldquo;release to the captives&rdquo; (Isa 61:1-2; Luke 4:18-19). Jesus inaugurates the ultimate homecoming — the restoration of humanity to God&rsquo;s presence — that the physical return from Babylon only foreshadowed.</p>",
    "2": "<p>&ldquo;The first to dwell again in their possessions in their cities&rdquo; — the returning remnant taking hold of their inheritance prefigures the promise of Heb 9:15: Christ is the mediator of the new covenant &ldquo;so that those who are called may receive the promised eternal inheritance.&rdquo; The physical return to ancestral cities is a type of the spiritual re-possession of all things in Christ — the meek inheriting the earth (Matt 5:5; Rom 4:13: Abraham&rsquo;s offspring heir of the <em>world</em>).</p>",
    "3": "<p>The returning community includes people from Judah, Benjamin, Ephraim, and Manasseh — representatives of the divided kingdom reunited in one city. The Chronicler&rsquo;s all-Israel theology reaches forward to Paul&rsquo;s vision of Christ as the one who &ldquo;has made us both one and has broken down in his flesh the dividing wall of hostility&rdquo; (Eph 2:14), creating one new humanity from the formerly divided people of God.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Uthai son of Ammihud, of the sons of Judah — the tribe of the lion, the royal line. Every Judahite name in the resettlement list carries the typological weight of Judah&rsquo;s calling as the tribe from which the scepter would not depart (Gen 49:10) until Shiloh comes. The remnant who return to Jerusalem are the thread of the Messianic lineage being preserved through exile — the Lion of Judah (Rev 5:5) would come from this restored community.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The Shelahites and Zerahites — subdivisions within Judah — represent the preserved remnant that survived exile. The pattern of remnant-preservation runs throughout Scripture: Noah&rsquo;s family, Lot from Sodom, the seven thousand who had not bowed to Baal (1 Kgs 19:18; Rom 11:4-5). Paul sees this remnant logic as the key to understanding Israel&rsquo;s partial hardening: &ldquo;a remnant chosen by grace&rdquo; (Rom 11:5) — and Christ himself is the ultimate remnant, the one faithful Israelite through whom the many are saved.</p>",
    "6": "<p>690 men of the Zerahite clans — a specific count that registers the precision of divine preservation. The Chronicler&rsquo;s careful numbering of the returned community reflects the same pastoral instinct that drives Jesus&rsquo; parable of the lost sheep (Luke 15:4-7): the shepherd who counts his flock, notes the missing one, and rejoices over each recovered individual. The census of the remnant is the Father counting his children home.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Sallu son of Meshullam — among the first Benjaminites to resettle Jerusalem. Benjamin&rsquo;s inclusion alongside Judah in the restored city reflects the covenantal unity preserved through exile. The tribe of Benjamin produced Saul (the failed king) and Paul (the apostle of grace) — bookends that frame the story of God working through the unlikely tribe. The remnant of Benjamin in Jerusalem points forward to the day when all the families of the earth will be gathered to the city of the great King (Ps 48:2; Rev 21:24).</p>",
    "8": "<p>Ibneiah, Elah son of Uzzi, Meshullam son of Shephatiah — the named Benjaminite returnees whose genealogies the Chronicler preserves. The specificity of naming signals that these individuals matter to God: the hairs of their heads are numbered (Matt 10:30). The Chronicler&rsquo;s practice of recording every name participates in the divine logic of the book of life (Rev 20:12; 21:27) — the names of the redeemed are not lost in the mass of history.</p>",
    "9": "<p>956 Benjaminite men — the returned remnant of the tribe whose first king had failed. The number is modest against the pre-exilic population, yet the Chronicler registers it with precision. The post-exilic community&rsquo;s small size is not defeat but the logic of the kingdom of God: the mustard seed, the pinch of yeast, the small stone that became a great mountain (Dan 2:35; Matt 13:31-33). Christ&rsquo;s kingdom begins as a remnant and fills the earth.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The priestly families — Jedaiah, Jehoiarib, Jachin — returned to serve in the rebuilt temple. Their return fulfills Ezekiel&rsquo;s vision of a restored priestly service (Ezek 44) and points forward to the permanent priestly ministry of Christ: &ldquo;he holds his priesthood permanently, because he continues forever&rdquo; (Heb 7:24). Every Levitical priest who served in the Second Temple was a living anticipation of the one great High Priest whose service never ends.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Azariah son of Hilkiah — a descendant of Zadok, serving as &ldquo;the chief officer of the house of God.&rdquo; The Zadokite chief priest at the center of the restored community points toward Christ&rsquo;s priestly kingship: as Zadok anointed Solomon (1 Kgs 1:39) and was established as the permanent high-priestly line, so Christ is both the anointing king and the eternal high priest — &ldquo;a priest forever after the order of Melchizedek&rdquo; (Ps 110:4; Heb 5:6), whose service encompasses and supersedes the Zadokite line.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Adaiah son of Jeroham — &ldquo;a mighty man of valor for the work of the service of the house of God&rdquo; — represents the priestly vocation as both strength and service. The priestly work of atonement required courage: entering the Most Holy Place was, for the high priest, a matter of life and death. Christ&rsquo;s priestly entry into the true Most Holy Place &ldquo;through his own blood&rdquo; (Heb 9:12) is the ultimate act of priestly courage — the one priest who could bear the weight of the world&rsquo;s sin and emerge victorious.</p>",
    "13": "<p>1,760 priests — mighty men for the work of the service of God&rsquo;s house. The priestly army of the Second Temple was the servant-corps of YHWH, their service an act of spiritual warfare as much as liturgy. Christ transforms this service: he makes his people &ldquo;a kingdom and priests to our God&rdquo; (Rev 5:10; 1 Pet 2:9) — the new covenant fulfillment where the whole people of God becomes a priestly nation, serving before the Father in Christ.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The Levites included Shemaiah son of Hasshub of the sons of Merari. The Merarite clan was responsible for the structural components of the Tabernacle (Num 3:36-37) — the heavy, load-bearing elements. Their temple service in the restoration period reflects the endurance of Levitical ministry through exile. The persistence of Levitical families in spite of seventy years of displacement testifies to God&rsquo;s faithfulness in preserving the instruments of his worship — as he would preserve and vindicate the ultimate Servant through death and resurrection.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Mattaniah, Bakbakkar, Heresh, Galal, Mattaniah son of Micah — the Levitical singers and their families. The naming of the musical families signals that praise is not incidental to the life of the returned community: it is structural. Hebrews 2:12 quotes Ps 22:22 as spoken by Christ: &ldquo;I will tell of your name to my brothers; in the midst of the congregation I will sing your praise&rdquo; — the Son leads the song of praise in the midst of the gathered community, fulfilling the Levitical choir&rsquo;s typological role.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Obadiah son of Shemaiah — a Levite. Obadiah means &ldquo;servant of YHWH&rdquo; — the name itself a microcosm of the Levitical calling that points to the ultimate Servant of YHWH (Isa 42:1-4; 52:13-53:12). The Levites as servants in God&rsquo;s house are a corporate type of the one Servant through whom Israel&rsquo;s mission is fulfilled.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The gatekeepers: Shallum, Akkub, Talmon, and Ahiman — &ldquo;Shallum was the chief.&rdquo; The gatekeeper&rsquo;s office guarded access to the divine presence in the temple. Jesus identifies himself as both the gate and the shepherd: &ldquo;I am the door of the sheep&rdquo; (John 10:7); &ldquo;the shepherd enters by the gate&rdquo; (John 10:2-3). The earthly gatekeepers who regulated who could enter God&rsquo;s house are types of Christ, the living door through whom all must pass to come to the Father (John 14:6).</p>",
    "18": "<p>The gatekeepers at the king&rsquo;s gate on the east — the primary gate of the temple precinct. The east-facing gate carries eschatological weight: Ezekiel&rsquo;s vision of YHWH&rsquo;s glory returning to the temple comes from the east (Ezek 43:2) through the gate that faces east (Ezek 44:1-2), and Jesus&rsquo; return is expected from the east (Matt 24:27). The gatekeepers at the east gate are unwitting participants in the eschatological drama of the divine return.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Shallum son of Kore, son of Ebiasaph — the gatekeeping clan whose ancestors had been keepers of the threshold of the tent. Their transgenerational faithfulness to a single calling across centuries of Israelite history points to the permanence of Christ&rsquo;s priestly-gatekeeper role: &ldquo;because he continues forever, he holds his priesthood permanently&rdquo; (Heb 7:24). No exile, no disruption can remove the one through whom access to God is secured.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Phinehas son of Eleazar was once their chief — &ldquo;the LORD was with him.&rdquo; Phinehas&rsquo; zeal that turned back divine wrath (Num 25:7-13; Ps 106:30-31) established a covenant of perpetual priesthood. His zeal typologically anticipates Christ&rsquo;s atoning work: as Phinehas&rsquo; single act of righteous intervention stopped the plague on Israel, Christ&rsquo;s single sacrifice &ldquo;put away sin&rdquo; once for all (Heb 9:26). The Chronicler&rsquo;s citation of Phinehas as historical precedent frames the gatekeepers within an atonement theology.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Zechariah son of Meshelemiah was the gatekeeper at the entrance of the tent of meeting. This Zechariah is listed among the gatekeepers who minister at the threshold between the holy and the common. Every such threshold in the Old Covenant pointed to the veil of the temple that was torn in two at Christ&rsquo;s death (Matt 27:51) — the moment when the barrier between God and his people was permanently removed, opening the &ldquo;new and living way&rdquo; through the torn flesh of Jesus (Heb 10:20).</p>",
    "22": "<p>212 gatekeepers — chosen and enrolled in David and Samuel&rsquo;s time — &ldquo;in their permanent office.&rdquo; David and Samuel jointly established this order, a prophetic-royal collaboration that points to Christ who is simultaneously prophet (Deut 18:18; Acts 3:22), priest (Heb 7:17), and king (Rev 19:16). The gatekeeper institution inaugurated by prophet and king reaches its fulfillment in the one who is prophet, priest, and king in himself — who declares himself &ldquo;the door.&rdquo;</p>",
    "23": "<p>The gatekeepers kept watch over the gates of the LORD&rsquo;s house — &ldquo;so they and their descendants were in charge of the gates of the house of the LORD.&rdquo; The intergenerational custody of the gates speaks of permanence and perpetual vigilance. Revelation&rsquo;s New Jerusalem has twelve gates that &ldquo;will never be shut by day — and there will be no night there&rdquo; (Rev 21:25) — the eschatological temple has gatekeepers but the gates are permanently open. Christ&rsquo;s work transforms the gatekeeper&rsquo;s office from exclusion to perpetual welcome.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The four directions of the gates — east, west, north, south — signal the universality of God&rsquo;s house. The temple is not a parochial regional shrine but the cosmic center accessible from every direction. Isaiah&rsquo;s vision of all nations streaming to Zion (Isa 2:2-3; 60:1-3) and Jesus&rsquo; declaration that &ldquo;many will come from east and west and recline at table&rdquo; in the kingdom (Matt 8:11) extend the four-directional gatekeeping to its universal fulfillment: people from every direction coming to the one who is the gate.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The gatekeepers&rsquo; villages — they would come in for seven-day rotations. The rotation principle meant the whole community shared in the sacred duty, not just a permanent professional class. This democratization of sacred service points toward the new covenant vision of a community where every member is a priest (1 Pet 2:9; Rev 1:6), where the Spirit falls on sons and daughters, old and young, servants male and female (Acts 2:17-18). The rotating gate-duty prefigures the shared priesthood of all believers.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The four chief gatekeepers — in charge of the chambers, the treasuries of the house of God. Their authority over the treasury points to Christ&rsquo;s role as the one in whom &ldquo;are hidden all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge&rdquo; (Col 2:3). The earthly treasury of the temple, guarded by faithful Levites, is a type of the inexhaustible riches of Christ — the ultimate treasury of the household of God.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The gatekeepers lodged around the house of God, for they were responsible for its guard; they opened it every morning. The daily discipline of opening the temple gates at dawn participates in the liturgical rhythm of morning sacrifice and praise that runs through the Psalter (Ps 5:3; 59:16; 88:13; 92:2; 130:6). Christ is &ldquo;the resurrection and the life&rdquo; (John 11:25) — the one who, on the morning of the first day of the week, opened the tomb-gate himself, declaring that the new temple is open to all.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Some of the gatekeepers were entrusted with the vessels used in worship — counting them when they were brought in and taken out. The careful accounting for sacred vessels reflects the principle of 2 Cor 4:7: &ldquo;we have this treasure in jars of clay, to show that the surpassing power belongs to God and not to us.&rdquo; Every sacred vessel in the temple pointed to its greater antitype — the body of Christ as the vessel of the divine glory (John 1:14; Col 2:9), and the church as the body that holds this treasure.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Others were entrusted with the furnishings, the sacred vessels, the fine flour, the wine, the oil, the incense, and the spices. The list of liturgical materials — flour, wine, oil, incense, spices — maps onto the elements of Christ&rsquo;s self-offering: the bread and cup of the Eucharist (Matt 26:26-28), the oil of the Spirit (Acts 10:38), the incense of his intercession (Rev 8:3-4), the fragrant offering of his sacrifice (Eph 5:2). Every element of the temple&rsquo;s material culture participates in the grammar of the cross.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Some of the priests mixed the ointment of the spices. The priestly blending of sacred oil and spices — a closely guarded formula (Exod 30:22-38, not to be replicated) — is the priestly act of consecration. Christ is the Anointed One (<em>Māšîaḥ</em>/<em>Christos</em>) — the one on whom the Spirit &ldquo;rested&rdquo; at his baptism (Isa 11:2; Matt 3:16) with the full weight of the divine anointing. The priestly blending of oils points to the Father&rsquo;s anointing of the Son &ldquo;with the oil of gladness beyond your companions&rdquo; (Ps 45:7; Heb 1:9).</p>",
    "31": "<p>Mattithiah the Levite, firstborn of Shallum the Korahite, was entrusted with the flat cakes. The baking of the <em>ḥăḇittîm</em> (flat grain cakes) was a daily offering made on the griddle by the priests (Lev 6:19-23). The daily bread offering — the perpetual presence of grain before YHWH — is the material sign that God provides and sustains life. Jesus teaches his disciples to pray for &ldquo;daily bread&rdquo; (Matt 6:11) and declares himself &ldquo;the bread of life&rdquo; (John 6:35) — the fulfillment of every grain offering laid before the LORD.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The Kohathite Levites were in charge of the showbread — the bread of the Presence (<em>leḥem happānîm</em>) — set out every Sabbath. Jesus cites David&rsquo;s eating of the showbread (1 Sam 21:1-6) in his defense of Sabbath mercy (Mark 2:25-28): &ldquo;the Son of Man is lord of the Sabbath.&rdquo; As David legitimately ate the bread of the Presence, Christ — the Son of David and lord of the Sabbath — fulfills the showbread&rsquo;s promise: he is the Bread of the Presence, the living bread that gives life to the world (John 6:51).</p>",
    "33": "<p>The singers, heads of Levitical families, were exempt from all other duties because they were on duty day and night. Continuous song before the LORD — the proto-liturgy of hours — anticipates the unceasing worship before the Lamb described in Revelation: &ldquo;day and night they never cease to say, Holy, holy, holy&rdquo; (Rev 4:8). The Levitical musicians&rsquo; perpetual service in the earthly temple is the shadow of the eternal song around the heavenly throne — the song of Moses and the Lamb (Rev 15:3).</p>",
    "34": "<p>These were the heads of the Levitical families, chief men, who lived in Jerusalem. The leadership structure of the Levitical guilds in the restored city models the ordered body that Paul describes for the church: &ldquo;God has appointed in the church first apostles, second prophets, third teachers&rdquo; (1 Cor 12:28) — each member with a specific function within the one body. The Levitical heads in Jerusalem prefigure the elders and overseers of the new covenant community who lead the priestly people.</p>",
    "35": "<p>Jeiel the father of Gibeon lived in Gibeon — the genealogy pivots back to introduce Saul. Gibeon was the city whose residents tricked Joshua into a covenant (Josh 9) and where the tabernacle stood during David&rsquo;s reign (1 Chr 16:39). The Gibeon-Saul connection is deliberately ominous: Saul later violated the Gibeonite covenant (2 Sam 21:1-2), bringing bloodguilt on Israel. The genealogy&rsquo;s return to Gibeon signals that the story of Saul is also the story of broken covenant — in contrast to David (and ultimately Christ) who kept covenant faithfully.</p>",
    "36": "<p>His firstborn son was Abdon, then Zur, Kish, Baal, Ner, Nadab — the roster of Saul&rsquo;s ancestors and relatives in Gibeon. The careful genealogy of the Saulide family serves a typological purpose in Chronicles: Saul is presented as the full negative foil to David, the king who embodied all that goes wrong when covenant faithfulness fails. As the first Adam fell and the second Adam succeeded, Saul the first king falls so that David the man after God&rsquo;s heart might establish the type of the coming King.</p>",
    "37": "<p>Gedor, Ahio, Zechariah, and Mikloth — the brothers and sons of Gibeonite Jeiel. The Saulide genealogy embeds Saul firmly in the patriarchal structure of a Benjaminite family — a legitimate tribal heir to Israel&rsquo;s early leadership, yet one whose story ends in catastrophic failure. Saul&rsquo;s failure is not presented as inevitable (YHWH warns him repeatedly) but as chosen — the accumulated result of self-reliance and disobedience. The contrast with David&rsquo;s response to failure (repentance, whole-hearted return) is the typological lesson that culminates in Christ&rsquo;s perfect obedience.</p>",
    "38": "<p>Mikloth fathered Shimeam — the genealogy continues down toward Saul. The ordinary succession of a Benjaminite family leading to the first king of Israel illustrates the Chronicler&rsquo;s consistent theme: God works through human genealogies and family structures, yet the outcome depends on the character of those who inherit the line. The contrast between Saul (who had the right genealogy but wrong heart) and David (chosen not by birth but by divine favor and whole-hearted devotion) anticipates Paul&rsquo;s argument that true sonship is of faith, not of flesh (Rom 9:6-8; Gal 3:7).</p>",
    "39": "<p>Ner fathered Kish, Kish fathered Saul; Saul fathered Jonathan, Malchishua, Abinadab, and Esh-baal. The Chronicler preserves &ldquo;Esh-baal&rdquo; (the original name = man of Baal, used as a personal name before Baal became purely a pagan title) where Samuel-Kings uses the euphemism Ish-bosheth (&ldquo;man of shame&rdquo;). The name-preservation signals that the Chronicler is giving a sober historical account, not a polemical revision. The Saulide dynasty that ends in Esh-baal&rsquo;s brief contested reign (2 Sam 2–4) is presented as a complete genealogical unit — a closed chapter.</p>",
    "40": "<p>Jonathan&rsquo;s son was Merib-baal (=Mephibosheth in 2 Sam 4:4) — &ldquo;and Merib-baal fathered Micah.&rdquo; Mephibosheth the crippled grandson of Saul whom David showed <em>ḥesed</em> (loyal love) for Jonathan&rsquo;s sake (2 Sam 9) is the OT&rsquo;s most vivid portrait of undeserved grace: the enemy&rsquo;s dependent, unable to walk, eating at the king&rsquo;s table for the rest of his life. He is a type of the sinner restored by grace — unable by nature to approach the King, invited to the Messianic banquet (Luke 14:21; Matt 22:9-10) through the covenant faithfulness of the one who made an oath to his father.</p>",
    "41": "<p>The sons of Micah included Pithon, Melech, Tahrea, and Ahaz — the genealogy continues beyond Mephibosheth into subsequent generations of the Saulide line that survived David&rsquo;s reign. David&rsquo;s preservation of Mephibosheth and his descendants demonstrates that the transfer of kingdom to David was not genocidal but covenantal — he showed mercy to his predecessor&rsquo;s family. The Davidic kingdom&rsquo;s coexistence with the remnant of Saul&rsquo;s house prefigures the new covenant&rsquo;s transformation of enemies into guests at the king&rsquo;s table.</p>",
    "42": "<p>And Ahaz fathered Jarah, and Jarah fathered Alemeth, Azmaveth, and Zimri — the Saulide genealogy eight generations deep after Saul himself. The persistence of the Saulide family line even as the kingdom has long since passed to David points to the paradox of divine patience: God does not destroy those whose representative failed; he preserves them and extends his mercy to them. The remnant of Benjamin, including the remnant of the Saulide family, will return from exile alongside Judah — the failed house does not end but is gathered with the faithful.</p>",
    "43": "<p>Zimri fathered Moza, Moza fathered Binea; and Rephaiah his son, Eleasah his son, Azel his son. The genealogy now reaches ten generations beyond Saul. The Chronicler&rsquo;s inclusion of this extended Saulide genealogy is a statement of hope as much as history: even the family of the failed king is not lost. God numbers every generation. The counting of names — even of those whose ancestor rejected God&rsquo;s covenant — testifies to the divine patience that &ldquo;is not wishing that any should perish, but that all should reach repentance&rdquo; (2 Pet 3:9).</p>",
    "44": "<p>Azel had six sons: Azrikam, Bocheru, Ishmael, Sheariah, Obadiah, and Hanan — Saul&rsquo;s line recorded to its sixth generation beyond Saul&rsquo;s death. The six sons of the last named Saulide form a complete generational unit — the number of completion in biblical numerology. The genealogy closes like a bookend: the Saulide line is complete, recorded, and preserved. Now ch10 will narrate how that dynasty ended, and ch11 how the Davidic dynasty began — the typological transfer from failed king to faithful king, from first Adam to second Adam.</p>"
  },
  "10": {
    "1": "<p>The Philistines fought against Israel, and the men of Israel fled before the Philistines and fell on Mount Gilboa. The battle of Gilboa is the hinge of 1 Chronicles: the genealogical prologue (chs 1–9) has established who Israel is; now the narrative begins with the death of the first king and the end of the old order. The pattern of defeat-and-restoration that governs the Chronicler&rsquo;s theology is here at its starkest: Israel in full flight before their enemies, the king about to die. The old order&rsquo;s collapse creates the space for the new — as Christ&rsquo;s death precedes resurrection, as Israel&rsquo;s exile precedes restoration.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The Philistines overtook Saul and his sons; and the Philistines struck down Jonathan and Abinadab and Malchishua, the sons of Saul. The three sons who die with their father complete the end of the Saulide royal line (Esh-baal/Ishbosheth survives but his brief contested reign is entirely omitted by the Chronicler). The death of Jonathan — David&rsquo;s covenant friend, the loyal son of the disloyal king — is especially poignant. Jonathan, who consistently chose David over his own dynastic interest (1 Sam 18:4; 23:17), perishes with the house that refused to acknowledge what Jonathan knew: YHWH had chosen David.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The battle pressed hard against Saul, and the archers found him, and he was wounded by the archers. Saul is brought down not by a warrior in hand-to-hand combat but by archers — by distant, impersonal projectiles. He cannot even die in the kind of battle he was supposed to fight. The contrast with David&rsquo;s single combat against Goliath is exact: David trusted YHWH and fought decisively; Saul trusted in military formation and was helplessly picked off from afar. The king who would not trust YHWH in life cannot be rescued by human means in death.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Saul said to his armor-bearer, &ldquo;Draw your sword and thrust me through with it, lest these uncircumcised come and mistreat me.&rdquo; But his armor-bearer would not, for he feared greatly. So Saul took his own sword and fell upon it. Saul&rsquo;s final act is self-destruction — the logical terminus of the trajectory of self-reliance that began with his first disobedience (1 Sam 13:8-14). He dies by his own sword, the weapon that could not save him from uncircumcised enemies. The contrast with Christ is absolute: where Saul chose death to escape humiliation, Jesus endured humiliation and suffering to the end, &ldquo;who for the joy that was set before him endured the cross, despising the shame&rdquo; (Heb 12:2).</p>",
    "5": "<p>When his armor-bearer saw that Saul was dead, he also fell upon his sword and died. Saul&rsquo;s death becomes the occasion of another death — the loyal servant killed not by the enemy but by the despair of his lord&rsquo;s defeat. The armor-bearer&rsquo;s suicide is the collateral tragedy of a kingdom built on the wrong foundation. The contrast with the disciples&rsquo; response to Christ&rsquo;s death — initial despair that becomes resurrection hope — marks the difference between a death that only brings more death and the death of the Son of God that brings life (John 12:24).</p>",
    "6": "<p>Thus Saul died; he and his three sons and all his house died together. The Chronicler adds &ldquo;and all his house&rdquo; — a phrase that goes beyond 1 Sam 31:6. The complete end of the Saulide royal household (in its fighting male members) is presented as the end of an era. The old order must completely end for the new to begin: as the old creation must pass away for the new creation to come (Rev 21:1; 2 Cor 5:17), as the old covenant must be superseded by the new (Heb 8:13), so the Saulide dynasty must completely fall for the Davidic kingdom to arise.</p>",
    "7": "<p>When all the men of Israel who were in the valley saw that they had fled and that Saul and his sons were dead, they abandoned their cities and fled, and the Philistines came and lived in them. The scattering of the sheep when the shepherd falls echoes Jesus&rsquo; quotation of Zech 13:7 at Gethsemane: &ldquo;I will strike the shepherd, and the sheep of the flock will be scattered&rdquo; (Matt 26:31). As Israel&rsquo;s defeat and scattering at Gilboa preceded the gathering under David, the disciples&rsquo; scattering at the cross preceded their gathering at Pentecost. The dispersion is not the end of the story.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The next day the Philistines came to strip the slain and found Saul and his sons fallen on Mount Gilboa. The despoiling of the fallen king&rsquo;s body — stripped of armor, trophy-beheaded in v9 — is the Philistines&rsquo; moment of apparent triumph. The image of an anointed king despoiled by enemies runs forward to the cross: the soldiers divided Jesus&rsquo; garments and cast lots (Matt 27:35; Ps 22:18). Yet as David restored Israel&rsquo;s honor after the Goliath battle reversed the stripping of the fallen, so Christ&rsquo;s resurrection reversed the apparent victory of his enemies.</p>",
    "9": "<p>They stripped him and took his head and his armor, and sent messengers throughout the land of the Philistines to carry the good news to their idols and to the people. The Philistines&rsquo; proclamation of &ldquo;good news&rdquo; (<em>ûlᵉḇaśśēr</em>) to their idols is a grotesque parody of the true <em>bᵉśōrāh</em> (good news/gospel) — the announcement of victory in God&rsquo;s name. The false gospel of Saul&rsquo;s defeat is answered by the true gospel of David&rsquo;s anointing — and ultimately by the true <em>euangelion</em> of Christ&rsquo;s resurrection, the announcement of the true King&rsquo;s victory over death, declared not to idols but to all the nations (Matt 28:18-20).</p>",
    "10": "<p>They put his armor in the house of their gods and fastened his head in the house of Dagon. Saul&rsquo;s armor placed in an idol&rsquo;s temple repeats the very indignity that Saul himself had inflicted — he had put Goliath&rsquo;s armor in his own tent (1 Sam 17:54) and now receives the same treatment from his enemies. The ironic reversal is characteristic of Chronicler theology: the proud are humbled, the disobedient receive what they gave. Yet Dagon himself had already been humiliated before the ark (1 Sam 5:1-7) — the idol that now receives Saul&rsquo;s armor is the god already proven powerless before YHWH.</p>",
    "11": "<p>When all Jabesh-gilead heard all that the Philistines had done to Saul, all the valiant men arose and took away the body of Saul and the bodies of his sons, and brought them to Jabesh. The men of Jabesh-gilead act in covenant faithfulness — remembering Saul&rsquo;s rescue of their city (1 Sam 11) by giving his body proper burial. Their act of loyal love for the fallen king is a type of the faithful disciples who took care of Jesus&rsquo; body (John 19:38-42; Mark 15:46) — acts of covenant devotion performed when hope seemed lost, which set the stage for the resurrection.</p>",
    "12": "<p>They buried their bones under the oak in Jabesh and fasted seven days. The seven-day fast — a full week of mourning — is the maximum mourning period (cf. Gen 50:10). The entire community participates in lamenting the fallen king. Even the failed king receives appropriate mourning: his dignity as YHWH&rsquo;s anointed is not erased by his failure. David himself would mourn Saul and Jonathan extravagantly (2 Sam 1:11-12). The respect for the dead king&rsquo;s body models the principle that even the broken and failed image-bearers of God retain their dignity — a dignity that the resurrection of the body (1 Cor 15:42-44) ultimately vindicates.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&ldquo;So Saul died for his unfaithfulness (<em>maʿal</em>) that he committed against the LORD, in that he did not keep the word of the LORD.&rdquo; The Chronicler&rsquo;s theological verdict — unique to 1 Chronicles, absent from 1 Sam 31 — names the root cause: <em>maʿal</em>, the key Chronistic term for covenant treachery (29x in Chronicles). Saul&rsquo;s <em>maʿal</em> consisted of consulting the medium at Endor (1 Sam 28) rather than seeking YHWH. The wages of covenant unfaithfulness is death (Rom 6:23) — and Saul&rsquo;s death is presented not as bad luck in battle but as the inevitable consequence of abandoning the one who had established him.</p>",
    "14": "<p>&ldquo;He did not seek (<em>dāraš</em>) the LORD; therefore he put him to death and turned the kingdom over to David son of Jesse.&rdquo; The Chronicler&rsquo;s final verdict pairs the negative (<em>lōʾ dāraš</em> — did not seek) with the positive transfer: YHWH himself executed the judgment and effected the succession. <em>Dāraš YHWH</em> (seeking/inquiring of the LORD) is the Chronicler&rsquo;s defining criterion for legitimate kingship — every king is evaluated by whether he sought YHWH. David is the king who sought YHWH; Solomon is charged to seek YHWH (28:9); Asa, Jehoshaphat, and Hezekiah are commended for seeking YHWH; Saul is the fundamental negative example. Christ is the ultimate &ldquo;seeker&rdquo; of the Father — the one who does only what he sees the Father doing (John 5:19), who &ldquo;learned obedience through what he suffered&rdquo; (Heb 5:8), and who at the cross cried &ldquo;My God, my God&rdquo; (Ps 22:1) — maintaining covenant relationship even in the darkness of abandonment. The kingdom that Saul forfeited by not seeking YHWH is given to David, and ultimately to the one who sought YHWH perfectly and received &ldquo;all authority in heaven and on earth&rdquo; (Matt 28:18).</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', '1chronicles')
    merge_comm(existing, CHRON1_CHRIST_9_10)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', '1chronicles', existing)
    print('1 Chronicles 9-10 christ layer written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
